messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /api/users/{id}

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- No

Accepted methods (based on the code, not assumptions):
- HEAD: No
- POST: No
- OPTIONS: No
- TRACE: No
- GET: Yes
- PUT: Yes
- DELETE: Yes
- PATCH: No

Explanation:
- server.js mounts the users router at the prefix /api/users via app.use('/api/users', userRoutes).
- routes/userRoutes.js defines a route for '/:id' and attaches handlers:
  - .delete(protect, admin, deleteUser)
  - .get(protect, admin, getUserById)
  - .put(protect, admin, updateUser)
  Therefore the GET handler for getUserById is reachable at the combined path /api/users/:id, which is expressed here as /api/users/{id}.
- There is no .all(...) call on this route that would allow all methods, so "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false.
- The code does not define explicit handlers for HEAD, POST, OPTIONS, TRACE, or PATCH on '/:id', so those are marked No. (Per your instruction, I did not rely on framework runtime behavior such as implicit HEAD/OPTIONS handling; only explicit route definitions in the code were considered.)
- GET, PUT, and DELETE are marked Yes because the router explicitly defines handlers for those methods on '/:id' (GET -> getUserById; PUT -> updateUser; DELETE -> deleteUser). All three are protected by the middleware protect and admin as shown in routes/userRoutes.js.
